@Andrzej 

There are seven one-color and seven striped color balls, plus the solid black eight ball. The three ball is solid red.

In public relations, information about someone or something is often "spun" to make the person or idea more attractive. A "straight shooter" is one that gives an honest opinion—one with "no spin".

@Steve L 

Tbh I didn't give it much thought. Other than the very few things I have learned from you and managed to remember (like RBI), American sports clues are automatic lookups for me: I just don't care about figuring them out as I don't find them interesting in the least. Had I thought about it, I suppose I would have realized it was about the number on the jersey. 

I am allergic to jersey numbers BTW. My wife watches a lot of football (soccer), and in recent years it has become customary for commentators to describe field positions with numbers. The guy who is supposed to score most goals is always called a nine (even though his jersey number can be whatever), and all the other guys get numbers, too. I don't get it though, and each time I hear something like "Oh, he is a classic three", I get irrationally irate. Yes, commentator, please, use your jargon, don't try to make me actually understand your sport...

@Al  in Pittsburgh 

Thanks, but the details are beyond me. What I meant was: why use the cryptic numbers in live commentary (the explanation of which numbers is as long as the one you linked) rather than call a guy a striker: a term that is understandable to more than just avid fans? When I watch climbing competitions, the commentators use climbing lingo but also keep explaining it all the time. Football (soccer) commentators just don't seem to care.

In case you're wondering why I'm so passionate about this: my wife likes football and so I'd like to like it, too, but things like that obnoxiously jargony commentary keep putting me off...

