@Lewis "I gave a side-eye to INSULATIONS"
Whenever I encounter these plurals of otherwise mass nouns, I try to imagine myself a store-manager giving direction to a stock-person: "Put the pestos on the top shelf, and the ribbons on the one below." 

For INSULATIONS, I imagined a contractor doing multiple installations, in different locations: "Our Guy put insulations under the main roof, as well as the west wing." Weird grammar, I know, and I probably wouldn't say it, but I can *imagine* it coming out of my mouth, in casual conversation.

